{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/building-sentence-embeddings-via-quick-thoughts-945484cae273", "time": 1682994286.910048, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/building-sentence-embeddings-via-quick-thoughts-945484cae273/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Building sentence embeddings via quick thoughts | by Edward Ma | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Building sentence embeddings via quick thoughts", "description": "In previous story, I shared skip-thoughts to compute a sentence embeddings. Today, we have another unsupervised learning approach to compute sentence embeddings which is Quick Thoughts. Logeswaran et\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/transforming-text-to-sentence-embeddings-layer-via-some-thoughts-b77bed60822c", "anchor_text": "skip-thoughts", "paragraph_index": 0}, {"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/transforming-text-to-sentence-embeddings-layer-via-some-thoughts-b77bed60822c", "anchor_text": "here", "paragraph_index": 5}, {"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/3-silver-bullets-of-word-embedding-in-nlp-10fa8f50cc5a", "anchor_text": "GloVe", "paragraph_index": 7}, {"url": "http://medium.com/@makcedward/", "anchor_text": "Medium Blog", "paragraph_index": 9}, {"url": "https://www.linkedin.com/in/edwardma1026", "anchor_text": "LinkedIn", "paragraph_index": 9}, {"url": "https://github.com/makcedward", "anchor_text": "Github", "paragraph_index": 9}, {"url": "https://arxiv.org/pdf/1803.02893.pdf", "anchor_text": "An efficient framework for learning sentence representations", "paragraph_index": 10}, {"url": "https://makcedward.github.io/", "anchor_text": "https://makcedward.github.io/", "paragraph_index": 12}], "all_paragraphs": ["In previous story, I shared skip-thoughts to compute a sentence embeddings. Today, we have another unsupervised learning approach to compute sentence embeddings which is Quick Thoughts.", "Logeswaran et al. (2018) introduced quick-thoughts approach to retrieve sentence embeddings for downstream application. After reading this article, you will understand:", "Quick-thoughts is quite similar to skip-thoughts. Rather than generating words to construct sentences (skip-thoughts approach), objective is classifying whether candidate sentences belongs to adjacent sentences. Same as skip-gram, both quick thoughts and skip-gram build leverage classifier to learn vectors.", "Giving a target sentence and using negative sampling approach (Mikolov et al., 2013) to construct a both valid context sentence and non-context sentences for a binary classifier.", "By labelling valid context sentence as target (e.g. 1) while other non-context sentences are labeled as non-target (e.g. 0), it can build a classifier to figure out which sentence is related to the target sentence.", "The architecture is same as skip-thoughts which use encoder and decoder approach but quick-thoughts use classifier instead of language model. You may check out here to understanding the architecture.", "From above result, you can noticed that QT (Quick Thoughts) got a quite good result in different tasks. uni-QT and bi-QT means using single directional and bi-directional RNN model.", "In supervised representation learning comparison, MC-QT (Multi Channel-Quick Thoughts) almost win in all tasks. MC-QT is defined as concatenation of two bi-directional RNNs. First bi-directional RNN use a pre-trained word vectors which is GloVe. Another bi-directional RNN is tunable word vectors which means training the vectors from scratch.", "In image-to-text and text-to-image downstream tasks, MC-QT also got a good result.", "I am Data Scientist in Bay Area. Focusing on state-of-the-art in Data Science, Artificial Intelligence , especially in NLP and platform related. You can reach me from Medium Blog, LinkedIn or Github.", "Logeswaran L., Lee H., 2018, An efficient framework for learning sentence representations", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "Focus in